Location of the Retina

Cornea: focus light.

Anterior Chamber: filled with aqueoushumor, focus light.

Pupil: opticalapeture.

Iris: varies pupil size.

Lens: variable focus.

Ciliary Body: accommodation (muscles to focus lens), production of aqueoushumor.

Posterior Chamber: filled with vitreoushumor, structural role.

Sclera: white fibrous tissue on outside of eye, structural.

Choroid: vascular layer.

Retina: neural layer: phototransduction and processing.

Optic Nerve: caries visual information to brain.Alsoblood vesselspassthroughthe optic disc.

Fovea: area of high visual acuity in primates, define by the foveal pit.

Laminar Organisation of theMammalian Retina

Laminar Organisation ofthe Mammalian Retina

5 broad classes of neuron, many layers.

Neurons:

    • Photoreceptors: Rod, Conephototransduction.
    • Bipolar and retinal ganglion cells process information in feedforward fashion
    • horizontal and amacrine cells process information in a lateral fashion.

Layers:

    • Outer/inner segments: phototransduction.
    • Nuclear layers: cell bodies.
    • Plexiform layers: synapses.
    • Nerve fibre layer: RGC axons that collect to form optic nerve.
    • Retina is contained by the retinal pigment epithelium and the inner limiting membraneon the outer and innersurfacerespectively.

Topographic Organisation of theMammalian Retina

Retinotopic organisationneighbouring cells respond to light fromneighbouring positions in the visual scene.

Central vision-> peripheral vision

    • Fovea-> macula-> periphery
    • High density of cells-> low density of cells.
    • Small dendritic tree-> largedendritictree

Foveal pit to allow direct light path to photoreceptors.

    • 50% retinal fibres
    • 2 degree of central vision
    • contains only cones
    • Required for reading etc.

Macula = Area centralis in other mammals with high resolution central area(e.g.cats).

Some mammals have no area of central high resolution (e.g.rodents).

Photoreceptors

    • S,M,L (primates), S,L (other mammals)
    • High acuity
    • colour

RodScotopic (night vision)

    • Low acuity
    • greyscale

Phototransduction

Phototransduction

Occurs in photoreceptor outer segment.

Mediated by

    • A membrane proteinopsin
      • Rodsrhodopsin
      • Conephotopsin(3 type in primates)
    • Achromaphore(light sensitive molecule)retinal

Absorption of a photon causes retinal to isomerise from the 11-cisform to the all-trans form. This initiates a biochemical cascadeinvolving G-protein coupled to Na+ channel.

    • During dark Na+ channel is open and cell is depolarizeddark current.
    • During light Na+ channel closes and cell is hyperpolarized.
    • No action potential, just graded potentials.

Bipolar Cells

9-11 types: parallel pathways.

3 major dichotomies + 1 polychotomy

    • ON/OFF: depolarised/hyperpolarised by light.
    • Transient/Sustained: flow fast/slow component of temporal modulation oflight.
    • S/M/L;Rod: tuning;type of photoreceptor input.
    • Diffuse/Confined: receptive field size, spatial extent of dendritic tree.

Bipolar Cells

OFF cells stratify in outer half of IPL

ON cells stratify in inner half of IPL

Transient cells stratify in middle of IPL

Sustained cells stratify in the margins of IPL.

Midget bipolar cells (primate retina)

    • In fovea: 1 M or L cone-> 1 MBC-> 1 MGC: private line to brain.
    • Basis for high acuity pathway.
    • Basis for RedGreen colour pathway.
    • Midget Theory of trichromacy: evolution of M cone after development ofprivate line because need to avoid mixing of colours.

Separate S ON bipolar cell and Rod bipolar cell.

ReceptiveFields

Derrington, Nature, 2001

(bipolar & RGC)

Centre-Surround Receptive Fields

Horizontal cells contribute to centre-surround receptive field organisation, vialateral inhibition.

    • ON-centre and OFF-surround.
    • OFF-centreand ON-surround.

These cells detect contrast.e.g.optimal stimulus for ON centre/OFF surround islight central spot with dark surround.

Contrast Sensitivity

Contrast Sensitivity

Contrast sensitivity:

    • Sensitivity to contrast in sinusoidal gratings.
    • Measured as inverse of contrast threshold.
    • Function of spatial frequency.
    • A result of centre-surround organisation inherited from bipolar cells.
    • Modelled with a difference-of-Gaussians.

Summary oftheMammalian Retina

  1. Cone-> Bipolar Cell-> Ganglion Cell
  2. ON and OFF pathways: ON and OFF GC
  3. Sustain and Transient pathways: Sustain andTransientretinal ganglion cell
  4. Primates:
    • midget pathways (confined): L(red) and M(green).Especially in foveal region of high acuity.
    • Parasol pathway (diffuse): non colour pathway
